  "signature": "ed25519:b1d4e7a92c053f68d1b3e0a74c2f895d3e1b6f0a2d9c4e7b1f3a0d6c8e2b5f9a",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) with documented QA processes and FDA-recognized validation history. Version control applied to all case files, boundary condition scripts, and post-processing routines. SQA level 2 requires documented version control and solver verification record.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is a commercially licensed solver with a comprehensive software quality management system compliant with ISO 9001. All simulation input files, UDF scripts, and mesh generation macros were archived under Git version control with tagged release at the time of submission. Solver verification benchmarks from the ASME V&V 20 suite were reviewed and confirmed applicable to incompressible turbulent internal flow regimes relevant to CPB pump operation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must reproduce canonical benchmark solutions (lid-driven cavity Re=1000, Poiseuille flow) within 1% of analytical or established reference values. Gradation 2 requires at least one published benchmark comparison documented in the submission record.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed by comparing ANSYS Fluent results against the lid-driven cavity benchmark at Re=1000 and fully developed Poiseuille flow in a circular duct. Velocity profiles agreed within 0.4% of the Ghia et al. reference solution. These benchmarks confirm that the discretization schemes and pressure-velocity coupling algorithm (SIMPLE) are correctly implemented for the flow regimes present in the CPB pump."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis required across at least three systematically refined mesh levels. GCI on the primary QoI (normalized hemolysis index) must be below 5% for Gradation 2; achieving Gradation 3 requires GCI below 2% with documented grid refinement ratio.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted using structured hexahedral meshes of 2.1M, 5.8M, and 14.2M cells, yielding a refinement ratio of approximately 1.4 between successive levels. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) was computed following Celik et al. (2008) on the normalized hemolysis index at the worst-case operating point (5 L/min, 3500 RPM). The fine-grid GCI was 1.3%, comfortably below the 2% threshold for Gradation 3. Near-wall resolution was confirmed with y+ < 1 throughout the impeller passage, consistent with the low-Reynolds SST k-ω turbulence model wall treatment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be documented with measured uncertainty bounds on flow rate (±2%), rotational speed (±1%), and fluid temperature (±0.5°C). Boundary conditions applied in the CFD model must be traceable to the reported experimental values.",
      "rationale": "Experimental flow conditions were drawn from the Morrison et al. (2019) dataset in which flow rate was controlled via a calibrated Coriolis meter (±1.5%), pump speed via an optical tachometer (±0.5%), and fluid temperature maintained at 37±0.3°C using a recirculating bath. These measured values were applied directly as CFD boundary conditions: mass-flow inlet, fixed rotational frame speed, and constant-temperature fluid properties at the measured operating temperature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index and pressure head must be compared against experimental measurements with quantitative agreement metrics (e.g., normalized RMS error, percent bias). Gradation 2 requires comparison at a minimum of three operating points with reported experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "CFD predictions of the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and pump pressure head were compared against experimental measurements at five flow-speed combinations. Normalized RMS error on NIH was 8.2% and on pressure head was 3.7%, both within experimental uncertainty bands. The relative hemolysis index RH remained below 1.0 at all assessed operating points, satisfying the COU acceptance criterion. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias in NIH prediction across the operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which is the clinically and regulatorily recognized metric for pump-induced red blood cell damage in CPB devices. NIH is directly linked to the COU decision (identification of worst-case hemolysis operating conditions) and is the quantity against which the predicate device comparison is made using the relative hemolysis index (RH). Secondary QoIs include pump pressure head and volumetric flow rate, which characterize the hydraulic operating envelope and ensure that hemolysis assessments are made at clinically relevant conditions. The selection of NIH as the primary QoI is consistent with FDA guidance on computational modeling of blood-contacting devices and with the ASME V&V 40 framework for cardiovascular device simulation. The model's ability to predict NIH with sufficient fidelity at Gradation 2 has been confirmed through the output comparison activity. The QoI is fully traceable from the device-level clinical risk (hemolysis leading to renal injury or transfusion requirement) through the engineering metric (NIH) to the computational output (volume-averaged scalar transport of the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model). This traceability chain was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team and is documented in the model development report MDR-CPB-2024-003. No alternative QoIs were identified that would provide materially different information for the COU decision, and the NIH metric has been validated for use with the power-law hemolysis model at the shear stress and exposure time ranges encountered in centrifugal CPB pumps operating between 2.5 and 6 L/min at speeds of 2500 to 4000 RPM. The relevance assessment concludes that the selected QoI is appropriate and sufficient for the intended regulatory decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be performed at conditions representative of the COU operating envelope. Gradation 2 requires that at least 60% of the validation test matrix falls within the COU operating range for each critical parameter (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties).",
      "rationale": "All five validation operating points (2.5, 3.5, 4.5, 5.0, and 6.0 L/min at speeds of 2500–4000 RPM) fall within the COU operating envelope for a Class II CPB device. The validation fluid (glycerol-water mixture at 37°C, viscosity 3.5 cP) matches the rheological properties of blood at the shear rates encountered in the impeller passage. Geometric similarity between the validation model and the production device geometry was confirmed within manufacturing tolerances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2 for this factor. Gradation 1 requires only that the solver is a commercially released product with published documentation; no independent solver error quantification is required.",
      "rationale": "At Model Risk Level 2, numerical solver error beyond code verification benchmarks is not required to be independently assessed. The use of a commercially released, widely validated CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent) satisfies the Gradation 1 requirement by default. Solver round-off and iterative convergence errors were monitored: residuals converged to below 1e-6 for all equations, and mass imbalance was below 0.01% in all cases."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 1 requires that simulation setup was performed by personnel with documented CFD training relevant to the application domain. No independent audit of simulation inputs is required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were set up and executed by engineers with a minimum of five years of experience in cardiovascular CFD and familiarity with ASME V&V 40 requirements. Simulation setup was peer-reviewed internally prior to submission. At MRL 2, no independent third-party audit of use error is required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model and hemolysis constitutive model must be justified by reference to published validation studies in comparable rotating blood-contacting device flows. Gradation 2 requires at least two published references demonstrating model form adequacy for the relevant flow regime.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on its demonstrated accuracy in predicting transitional and mildly turbulent flows in centrifugal pump geometries, as documented by Wiegmann et al. (2018) and Fraser et al. (2011) for blood pump applications. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was selected as the constitutive relation for red blood cell damage, consistent with its widespread use and validation in FDA-reviewed CFD submissions for blood-contacting devices. Model form uncertainty associated with turbulence closure was assessed as low given the predominantly laminar-to-transitional flow regime in the impeller passage at the assessed operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (blood viscosity, density) and geometric inputs must be documented with sources and uncertainty estimates. Gradation 2 requires that input uncertainty has been characterized for the two most sensitive model parameters as identified by a local sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Fluid density (1060 kg/m³) and dynamic viscosity (3.5 cP at 37°C) were taken from published rheological data for human blood at the shear rates encountered in CPB pumps. Geometric inputs were derived from the FDA-released generic centrifugal pump CAD model with dimensional tolerances of ±0.05 mm applied in the sensitivity study. A local sensitivity analysis identified impeller tip clearance and blade exit angle as the two most influential geometric parameters; these were varied across their manufacturing tolerance range and the resulting NIH variation was less than 4%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 1 requires only that the experimental samples used for validation are described in terms of geometry and material. No statistical characterization of sample variability is required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "The validation experiments used a single FDA generic centrifugal pump prototype fabricated to the published nominal geometry. At MRL 2, sample-to-sample variability assessment is not required. The prototype was inspected dimensionally prior to testing and confirmed to be within ±0.08 mm of the nominal CAD dimensions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Gradation 1 requires a qualitative statement that the model input parameters used in the validation activities are equivalent to those applicable in the COU. No quantitative equivalency mapping is required at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "The input parameters used in the validation simulations (geometry, fluid properties, boundary conditions) are equivalent to those applicable in the COU. The FDA generic pump geometry is representative of the Class II CPB device class. Fluid properties match blood-analog conditions used in regulatory hemolysis testing. Operating flow rates and speeds span the COU envelope. No material differences in input parameter space between validation and COU conditions were identified."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cpb-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels at Model Risk Level 2. Six factors were not assessed, consistent with MRL 2 requirements under ASME V&V 40-2018. The CFD model demonstrates sufficient credibility for use in identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device. The relative hemolysis index RH < 1 at all assessed operating points satisfies the COU acceptance criterion. The credibility assessment team concludes that the model is fit for the intended regulatory purpose.",
